105 // This can only handle non-void readnone functions. ----
106 // Also handled are constrained intrinsic that look like the types ----
107 // of instruction handled below (UnaryOperator, etc.). ----

110 switch ((Intrinsic::ID)F->getIntrinsicID()) { 0
111 case Intrinsic::experimental_constrained_fadd: 0
112 case Intrinsic::experimental_constrained_fsub: ----
113 case Intrinsic::experimental_constrained_fmul: ----
114 case Intrinsic::experimental_constrained_fdiv: ----
115 case Intrinsic::experimental_constrained_frem: ----
116 case Intrinsic::experimental_constrained_fptosi: ----

123 if (CFP->getExceptionBehavior() && 0

125 return false; 0

173 /// Match a 'select' including an optional 'not's of the condition. ----
174 static bool matchSelectWithOptionalNotCond(Value *V, Value *&Cond, Value *&A, 0
175 Value *&B, ----
176 SelectPatternFlavor &Flavor) { ----
177 // Return false if V is not even a select. ----
178 if (!match(V, m_Select(m_Value(Cond), m_Value(A), m_Value(B)))) 0
179 return false; 0
180 ----
181 // Look through a 'not' of the condition operand by swapping A/B. ----
182 Value *CondNot; ----
183 if (match(Cond, m_Not(m_Value(CondNot)))) { 0
184 Cond = CondNot; 0
185 std::swap(A, B); 0
186 } ----
187 ----
188 // Match canonical forms of min/max. We are not using ValueTracking's ----
189 // more powerful matchSelectPattern() because it may rely on instruction flags ----
190 // such as "nsw". That would be incompatible with the current hashing ----
191 // mechanism that may remove flags to increase the likelihood of CSE. ----
192 ----
193 Flavor = SPF_UNKNOWN; 0
194 CmpInst::Predicate Pred; ----
195 ----
196 if (!match(Cond, m_ICmp(Pred, m_Specific(A), m_Specific(B)))) { 0
197 // Check for commuted variants of min/max by swapping predicate. ----
198 // If we do not match the standard or commuted patterns, this is not a ----
199 // recognized form of min/max, but it is still a select, so return true. ----
200 if (!match(Cond, m_ICmp(Pred, m_Specific(B), m_Specific(A)))) 0
201 return true; 0
202 Pred = ICmpInst::getSwappedPredicate(Pred); 0
203 } ----
204 ----
205 switch (Pred) { 0
206 case CmpInst::ICMP_UGT: Flavor = SPF_UMAX; break; 0
207 case CmpInst::ICMP_ULT: Flavor = SPF_UMIN; break; 0
208 case CmpInst::ICMP_SGT: Flavor = SPF_SMAX; break; 0
209 case CmpInst::ICMP_SLT: Flavor = SPF_SMIN; break; 0
210 // Non-strict inequalities. ----
211 case CmpInst::ICMP_ULE: Flavor = SPF_UMIN; break; 0
212 case CmpInst::ICMP_UGE: Flavor = SPF_UMAX; break; 0
213 case CmpInst::ICMP_SLE: Flavor = SPF_SMIN; break; 0
214 case CmpInst::ICMP_SGE: Flavor = SPF_SMAX; break; 0
215 default: break; 0
216 } ----
217 ----
218 return true; 0
219 } ----

221 static unsigned hashCallInst(CallInst *CI) { 0
222 // Don't CSE convergent calls in different basic blocks, because they ----
223 // implicitly depend on the set of threads that is currently executing. ----
224 if (CI->isConvergent()) { 0
225 return hash_combine( 0
226 CI->getOpcode(), CI->getParent(), 0
227 hash_combine_range(CI->value_op_begin(), CI->value_op_end())); 0
228 } ----
229 return hash_combine( 0
230 CI->getOpcode(), 0
231 hash_combine_range(CI->value_op_begin(), CI->value_op_end())); 0
232 } ----

234 static unsigned getHashValueImpl(SimpleValue Val) { 0
235 Instruction *Inst = Val.Inst; 0
236 // Hash in all of the operands as pointers. ----
237 if (BinaryOperator *BinOp = dyn_cast(Inst)) { 0
238 Value *LHS = BinOp->getOperand(0); 0
239 Value *RHS = BinOp->getOperand(1); 0
240 if (BinOp->isCommutative() && BinOp->getOperand(0) > BinOp->getOperand(1)) 0
241 std::swap(LHS, RHS); 0
242 ----
243 return hash_combine(BinOp->getOpcode(), LHS, RHS); 0
244 } ----
245 ----
246 if (CmpInst *CI = dyn_cast(Inst)) { 0
247 // Compares can be commuted by swapping the comparands and ----
248 // updating the predicate. Choose the form that has the ----
249 // comparands in sorted order, or in the case of a tie, the ----
250 // one with the lower predicate. ----
251 Value *LHS = CI->getOperand(0); 0
252 Value *RHS = CI->getOperand(1); 0
253 CmpInst::Predicate Pred = CI->getPredicate(); 0
254 CmpInst::Predicate SwappedPred = CI->getSwappedPredicate(); 0
255 if (std::tie(LHS, Pred) > std::tie(RHS, SwappedPred)) { 0
256 std::swap(LHS, RHS); 0
257 Pred = SwappedPred; 0
258 } ----
259 return hash_combine(Inst->getOpcode(), Pred, LHS, RHS); 0
260 } ----
261 ----
262 // Hash general selects to allow matching commuted true/false operands. ----
263 SelectPatternFlavor SPF; ----
264 Value *Cond, *A, *B; ----
265 if (matchSelectWithOptionalNotCond(Inst, Cond, A, B, SPF)) { 0
266 // Hash min/max (cmp + select) to allow for commuted operands. ----
267 // Min/max may also have non-canonical compare predicate (eg, the compare for ----
268 // smin may use 'sgt' rather than 'slt'), and non-canonical operands in the ----
269 // compare. ----
270 // TODO: We should also detect FP min/max. ----
271 if (SPF == SPF_SMIN || SPF == SPF_SMAX || 0
272 SPF == SPF_UMIN || SPF == SPF_UMAX) { 0
273 if (A > B) 0
274 std::swap(A, B); 0
275 return hash_combine(Inst->getOpcode(), SPF, A, B); 0
276 } ----
277 ----
278 // Hash general selects to allow matching commuted true/false operands. ----
279 ----
280 // If we do not have a compare as the condition, just hash in the condition. ----
281 CmpInst::Predicate Pred; ----
282 Value *X, *Y; ----
283 if (!match(Cond, m_Cmp(Pred, m_Value(X), m_Value(Y)))) 0
284 return hash_combine(Inst->getOpcode(), Cond, A, B); 0
285 ----
286 // Similar to cmp normalization (above) - canonicalize the predicate value: ----
287 // select (icmp Pred, X, Y), A, B --> select (icmp InvPred, X, Y), B, A ----
288 if (CmpInst::getInversePredicate(Pred) < Pred) { 0
289 Pred = CmpInst::getInversePredicate(Pred); 0
290 std::swap(A, B); 0
291 } ----
292 return hash_combine(Inst->getOpcode(), Pred, X, Y, A, B); 0
293 } ----
294 ----
295 if (CastInst *CI = dyn_cast(Inst)) 0
296 return hash_combine(CI->getOpcode(), CI->getType(), CI->getOperand(0)); 0
297 ----
298 if (FreezeInst *FI = dyn_cast(Inst)) 0
299 return hash_combine(FI->getOpcode(), FI->getOperand(0)); 0
300 ----
301 if (const ExtractValueInst *EVI = dyn_cast(Inst)) 0
302 return hash_combine(EVI->getOpcode(), EVI->getOperand(0), 0
303 hash_combine_range(EVI->idx_begin(), EVI->idx_end())); 0
304 ----
305 if (const InsertValueInst *IVI = dyn_cast(Inst)) 0
306 return hash_combine(IVI->getOpcode(), IVI->getOperand(0), 0
307 IVI->getOperand(1), 0
308 hash_combine_range(IVI->idx_begin(), IVI->idx_end())); 0
309 ----
310 assert((isa(Inst) || isa(Inst) || 0
311 isa(Inst) || isa(Inst) || ----
312 isa(Inst) || isa(Inst) || ----
313 isa(Inst)) && ----
314 "Invalid/unknown instruction"); ----
315 ----
316 // Handle intrinsics with commutative operands. ----
317 // TODO: Extend this to handle intrinsics with >2 operands where the 1st ----
318 // 2 operands are commutative. ----
319 auto *II = dyn_cast(Inst); 0
320 if (II && II->isCommutative() && II->arg_size() == 2) { 0
321 Value *LHS = II->getArgOperand(0), *RHS = II->getArgOperand(1); 0
322 if (LHS > RHS) 0
323 std::swap(LHS, RHS); 0
324 return hash_combine(II->getOpcode(), LHS, RHS); 0
325 } ----
326 ----
327 // gc.relocate is 'special' call: its second and third operands are ----
328 // not real values, but indices into statepoint's argument list. ----
329 // Get values they point to. ----
330 if (const GCRelocateInst *GCR = dyn_cast(Inst)) 0
331 return hash_combine(GCR->getOpcode(), GCR->getOperand(0), 0
332 GCR->getBasePtr(), GCR->getDerivedPtr()); 0
333 ----
334 // Don't CSE convergent calls in different basic blocks, because they ----
335 // implicitly depend on the set of threads that is currently executing. ----
336 if (CallInst *CI = dyn_cast(Inst)) 0
337 return hashCallInst(CI); 0
338 ----
339 // Mix in the opcode. ----
340 return hash_combine( 0
341 Inst->getOpcode(), 0
342 hash_combine_range(Inst->value_op_begin(), Inst->value_op_end())); 0
343 } ----

345 unsigned DenseMapInfo::getHashValue(SimpleValue Val) { 0
346 #ifndef NDEBUG ----
347 // If -earlycse-debug-hash was specified, return a constant -- this ----
348 // will force all hashing to collide, so we'll exhaustively search ----
349 // the table for a match, and the assertion in isEqual will fire if ----
350 // there's a bug causing equal keys to hash differently. ----
351 if (EarlyCSEDebugHash) 0
352 return 0; 0
353 #endif ----
354 return getHashValueImpl(Val); 0
355 } ----

357 static bool isEqualImpl(SimpleValue LHS, SimpleValue RHS) { 0
358 Instruction *LHSI = LHS.Inst, *RHSI = RHS.Inst; 0
359 ----
360 if (LHS.isSentinel() || RHS.isSentinel()) 0
361 return LHSI == RHSI; 0
362 ----
363 if (LHSI->getOpcode() != RHSI->getOpcode()) 0
364 return false; 0
365 if (LHSI->isIdenticalToWhenDefined(RHSI)) { 0
366 // Convergent calls implicitly depend on the set of threads that is ----
367 // currently executing, so conservatively return false if they are in ----
368 // different basic blocks. ----
369 if (CallInst *CI = dyn_cast(LHSI); 0
370 CI && CI->isConvergent() && LHSI->getParent() != RHSI->getParent()) 0
371 return false; 0
372 ----
373 return true; 0
374 } ----
375 ----
376 // If we're not strictly identical, we still might be a commutable instruction ----
377 if (BinaryOperator *LHSBinOp = dyn_cast(LHSI)) { 0
378 if (!LHSBinOp->isCommutative()) 0
379 return false; 0
380 ----
381 assert(isa(RHSI) && 0
382 "same opcode, but different instruction type?"); ----
383 BinaryOperator *RHSBinOp = cast(RHSI); 0
384 ----
385 // Commuted equality ----
386 return LHSBinOp->getOperand(0) == RHSBinOp->getOperand(1) && 0
387 LHSBinOp->getOperand(1) == RHSBinOp->getOperand(0); 0
388 } ----
389 if (CmpInst *LHSCmp = dyn_cast(LHSI)) { 0
390 assert(isa(RHSI) && 0
391 "same opcode, but different instruction type?"); ----
392 CmpInst *RHSCmp = cast(RHSI); 0
393 // Commuted equality ----
394 return LHSCmp->getOperand(0) == RHSCmp->getOperand(1) && 0
395 LHSCmp->getOperand(1) == RHSCmp->getOperand(0) && 0
396 LHSCmp->getSwappedPredicate() == RHSCmp->getPredicate(); 0
397 } ----
398 ----
399 // TODO: Extend this for >2 args by matching the trailing N-2 args. ----
400 auto *LII = dyn_cast(LHSI); 0
401 auto *RII = dyn_cast(RHSI); 0
402 if (LII && RII && LII->getIntrinsicID() == RII->getIntrinsicID() && 0
403 LII->isCommutative() && LII->arg_size() == 2) { 0
404 return LII->getArgOperand(0) == RII->getArgOperand(1) && 0
405 LII->getArgOperand(1) == RII->getArgOperand(0); 0
406 } ----
407 ----
408 // See comment above in `getHashValue()`. ----
409 if (const GCRelocateInst *GCR1 = dyn_cast(LHSI)) 0
410 if (const GCRelocateInst *GCR2 = dyn_cast(RHSI)) 0
411 return GCR1->getOperand(0) == GCR2->getOperand(0) && 0
412 GCR1->getBasePtr() == GCR2->getBasePtr() && 0
413 GCR1->getDerivedPtr() == GCR2->getDerivedPtr(); 0
414 ----
415 // Min/max can occur with commuted operands, non-canonical predicates, ----
416 // and/or non-canonical operands. ----
417 // Selects can be non-trivially equivalent via inverted conditions and swaps. ----
418 SelectPatternFlavor LSPF, RSPF; ----
419 Value *CondL, *CondR, *LHSA, *RHSA, *LHSB, *RHSB; ----
420 if (matchSelectWithOptionalNotCond(LHSI, CondL, LHSA, LHSB, LSPF) && 0
421 matchSelectWithOptionalNotCond(RHSI, CondR, RHSA, RHSB, RSPF)) { 0
422 if (LSPF == RSPF) { 0
423 // TODO: We should also detect FP min/max. ----
424 if (LSPF == SPF_SMIN || LSPF == SPF_SMAX || 0
425 LSPF == SPF_UMIN || LSPF == SPF_UMAX) 0
426 return ((LHSA == RHSA && LHSB == RHSB) || 0
427 (LHSA == RHSB && LHSB == RHSA)); 0
428 ----
429 // select Cond, A, B <--> select not(Cond), B, A ----
430 if (CondL == CondR && LHSA == RHSA && LHSB == RHSB) 0
431 return true; 0
432 } ----
433 ----
434 // If the true/false operands are swapped and the conditions are compares ----
435 // with inverted predicates, the selects are equal: ----
436 // select (icmp Pred, X, Y), A, B <--> select (icmp InvPred, X, Y), B, A ----
437 // ----
438 // This also handles patterns with a double-negation in the sense of not + ----
439 // inverse, because we looked through a 'not' in the matching function and ----
440 // swapped A/B: ----
441 // select (cmp Pred, X, Y), A, B <--> select (not (cmp InvPred, X, Y)), B, A ----
442 // ----
443 // This intentionally does NOT handle patterns with a double-negation in ----
444 // the sense of not + not, because doing so could result in values ----
445 // comparing ----
446 // as equal that hash differently in the min/max cases like: ----
447 // select (cmp slt, X, Y), X, Y <--> select (not (not (cmp slt, X, Y))), X, Y ----
448 // ^ hashes as min ^ would not hash as min ----
449 // In the context of the EarlyCSE pass, however, such cases never reach ----
450 // this code, as we simplify the double-negation before hashing the second ----
451 // select (and so still succeed at CSEing them). ----
452 if (LHSA == RHSB && LHSB == RHSA) { 0
453 CmpInst::Predicate PredL, PredR; ----
454 Value *X, *Y; ----
455 if (match(CondL, m_Cmp(PredL, m_Value(X), m_Value(Y))) && 0
456 match(CondR, m_Cmp(PredR, m_Specific(X), m_Specific(Y))) && 0
457 CmpInst::getInversePredicate(PredL) == PredR) 0
458 return true; 0
459 } ----
460 } ----
461 ----
462 return false; 0
463 } ----
464 ----
465 bool DenseMapInfo::isEqual(SimpleValue LHS, SimpleValue RHS) { 0
466 // These comparisons are nontrivial, so assert that equality implies ----
467 // hash equality (DenseMap demands this as an invariant). ----
468 bool Result = isEqualImpl(LHS, RHS); 0
469 assert(!Result || (LHS.isSentinel() && LHS.Inst == RHS.Inst) || 0
470 getHashValueImpl(LHS) == getHashValueImpl(RHS)); ----
471 return Result; 0
472 } ----

480 /// Struct representing the available call values in the scoped hash ----

482 struct CallValue { ----
483 Instruction *Inst; ----
484 ----
485 CallValue(Instruction *I) : Inst(I) { 0
486 assert((isSentinel() || canHandle(I)) && "Inst can't be handled!"); 0
487 } 0
488 ----
489 bool isSentinel() const { 0
490 return Inst == DenseMapInfo::getEmptyKey() || 0
491 Inst == DenseMapInfo::getTombstoneKey(); 0
492 } ----
493 ----
494 static bool canHandle(Instruction *Inst) { 0
495 // Don't value number anything that returns void. ----
496 if (Inst->getType()->isVoidTy()) 0
497 return false; 0
498 ----
499 CallInst *CI = dyn_cast(Inst); 0
500 if (!CI || !CI->onlyReadsMemory() || 0
501 // FIXME: Currently the calls which may access the thread id may ----
502 // be considered as not accessing the memory. But this is ----
503 // problematic for coroutines, since coroutines may resume in a ----
504 // different thread. So we disable the optimization here for the ----
505 // correctness. However, it may block many other correct ----
506 // optimizations. Revert this one when we detect the memory ----
507 // accessing kind more precisely. ----
508 CI->getFunction()->isPresplitCoroutine()) 0
509 return false; 0
510 return true; 0
511 } ----
512 }; ----

533 unsigned DenseMapInfo::getHashValue(CallValue Val) { 0
534 Instruction *Inst = Val.Inst; 0
535 ----
536 // Hash all of the operands as pointers and mix in the opcode. ----
537 return hashCallInst(cast(Inst)); 0

539 ----
540 bool DenseMapInfo::isEqual(CallValue LHS, CallValue RHS) { 0
541 if (LHS.isSentinel() || RHS.isSentinel()) 0
542 return LHS.Inst == RHS.Inst; 0
543 ----
544 CallInst *LHSI = cast(LHS.Inst); 0
545 CallInst *RHSI = cast(RHS.Inst); 0
546 ----
547 // Convergent calls implicitly depend on the set of threads that is ----
548 // currently executing, so conservatively return false if they are in ----
549 // different basic blocks. ----
550 if (LHSI->isConvergent() && LHSI->getParent() != RHSI->getParent()) 0
551 return false; 0
552 ----
553 return LHSI->isIdenticalTo(RHSI); 0

557 // EarlyCSE implementation ----
558 //===----------------------------------------------------------------------===// ----

560 namespace { ----
561 ----
562 /// A simple and fast domtree-based CSE pass. ----
563 /// ----
564 /// This pass does a simple depth-first walk over the dominator tree, ----
565 /// eliminating trivially redundant instructions and using instsimplify to ----
566 /// canonicalize things as it goes. It is intended to be fast and catch obvious ----
567 /// cases so that instcombine and other passes are more effective. It is ----
568 /// expected that a later pass of GVN will catch the interesting/hard cases. ----
569 class EarlyCSE { ----
570 public: ----
571 const TargetLibraryInfo &TLI; ----
572 const TargetTransformInfo &TTI; ----
573 DominatorTree &DT; ----
574 AssumptionCache &AC; ----
575 const SimplifyQuery SQ; ----
576 MemorySSA *MSSA; ----
577 std::unique_ptr MSSAUpdater; ----
578 ----
579 using AllocatorTy = ----
580 RecyclingAllocator ----
581 ScopedHashTableVal>; ----
582 using ScopedHTType = ----
583 ScopedHashTable, ----
584 AllocatorTy>; ----
585 ----
586 /// A scoped hash table of the current values of all of our simple ----
587 /// scalar expressions. ----
588 /// ----
589 /// As we walk down the domtree, we look to see if instructions are in this: ----
590 /// if so, we replace them with what we find, otherwise we insert them so ----
591 /// that dominated values can succeed in their lookup. ----
592 ScopedHTType AvailableValues; ----
593 ----
594 /// A scoped hash table of the current values of previously encountered ----
595 /// memory locations. ----
596 /// ----
597 /// This allows us to get efficient access to dominating loads or stores when ----
598 /// we have a fully redundant load. In addition to the most recent load, we ----
599 /// keep track of a generation count of the read, which is compared against ----
600 /// the current generation count. The current generation count is incremented ----
601 /// after every possibly writing memory operation, which ensures that we only ----
602 /// CSE loads with other loads that have no intervening store. Ordering ----
603 /// events (such as fences or atomic instructions) increment the generation ----
604 /// count as well; essentially, we model these as writes to all possible ----
605 /// locations. Note that atomic and/or volatile loads and stores can be ----
606 /// present the table; it is the responsibility of the consumer to inspect ----
607 /// the atomicity/volatility if needed. ----
608 struct LoadValue { ----
609 Instruction *DefInst = nullptr; ----
610 unsigned Generation = 0; ----
611 int MatchingId = -1; ----
612 bool IsAtomic = false; ----
613 bool IsLoad = false; ----
614 ----
615 LoadValue() = default; 0
616 LoadValue(Instruction *Inst, unsigned Generation, unsigned MatchingId, 0
617 bool IsAtomic, bool IsLoad) ----
618 : DefInst(Inst), Generation(Generation), MatchingId(MatchingId), 0
619 IsAtomic(IsAtomic), IsLoad(IsLoad) {} 0
620 }; ----
621 ----
622 using LoadMapAllocator = ----
623 RecyclingAllocator ----
624 ScopedHashTableVal>; ----
625 using LoadHTType = ----
626 ScopedHashTable, ----
627 LoadMapAllocator>; ----
628 ----
629 LoadHTType AvailableLoads; ----
630 ----
631 // A scoped hash table mapping memory locations (represented as typed ----
632 // addresses) to generation numbers at which that memory location became ----
633 // (henceforth indefinitely) invariant. ----
634 using InvariantMapAllocator = ----
635 RecyclingAllocator ----
636 ScopedHashTableVal>; ----
637 using InvariantHTType = ----
638 ScopedHashTable, ----
639 InvariantMapAllocator>; ----
640 InvariantHTType AvailableInvariants; ----
641 ----
642 /// A scoped hash table of the current values of read-only call ----
643 /// values. ----
644 /// ----
645 /// It uses the same generation count as loads. ----
646 using CallHTType = ----
647 ScopedHashTable>; ----
648 CallHTType AvailableCalls; ----
649 ----
650 /// This is the current generation of the memory value. ----
651 unsigned CurrentGeneration = 0; ----
652 ----
653 /// Set up the EarlyCSE runner for a particular function. ----
654 EarlyCSE(const DataLayout &DL, const TargetLibraryInfo &TLI, 0
655 const TargetTransformInfo &TTI, DominatorTree &DT, ----
656 AssumptionCache &AC, MemorySSA *MSSA) ----
657 : TLI(TLI), TTI(TTI), DT(DT), AC(AC), SQ(DL, &TLI, &DT, &AC), MSSA(MSSA), 0
658 MSSAUpdater(std::make_unique(MSSA)) {} 0
659 ----
660 bool run(); ----
661 ----
662 private: ----
663 unsigned ClobberCounter = 0; ----
664 // Almost a POD, but needs to call the constructors for the scoped hash ----
665 // tables so that a new scope gets pushed on. These are RAII so that the ----
666 // scope gets popped when the NodeScope is destroyed. ----
667 class NodeScope { ----
668 public: ----
669 NodeScope(ScopedHTType &AvailableValues, LoadHTType &AvailableLoads, 0
670 InvariantHTType &AvailableInvariants, CallHTType &AvailableCalls) ----
671 : Scope(AvailableValues), LoadScope(AvailableLoads), 0
672 InvariantScope(AvailableInvariants), CallScope(AvailableCalls) {} 0
673 NodeScope(const NodeScope &) = delete; ----
674 NodeScope &operator=(const NodeScope &) = delete; ----
675 ----
676 private: ----
677 ScopedHTType::ScopeTy Scope; ----
678 LoadHTType::ScopeTy LoadScope; ----
679 InvariantHTType::ScopeTy InvariantScope; ----
680 CallHTType::ScopeTy CallScope; ----
681 }; ----

683 // Contains all the needed information to create a stack for doing a depth ----
684 // first traversal of the tree. This includes scopes for values, loads, and ----
685 // calls as well as the generation. There is a child iterator so that the ----
686 // children do not need to be store separately. ----
687 class StackNode { ----
688 public: ----
689 StackNode(ScopedHTType &AvailableValues, LoadHTType &AvailableLoads, 0
690 InvariantHTType &AvailableInvariants, CallHTType &AvailableCalls, ----
691 unsigned cg, DomTreeNode *n, DomTreeNode::const_iterator child, ----
692 DomTreeNode::const_iterator end) ----
693 : CurrentGeneration(cg), ChildGeneration(cg), Node(n), ChildIter(child), 0
694 EndIter(end), 0
695 Scopes(AvailableValues, AvailableLoads, AvailableInvariants, 0
696 AvailableCalls) 0
697 {} 0
698 StackNode(const StackNode &) = delete; ----
699 StackNode &operator=(const StackNode &) = delete; ----
700 ----
701 // Accessors. ----
702 unsigned currentGeneration() const { return CurrentGeneration; } 0
703 unsigned childGeneration() const { return ChildGeneration; } 0
704 void childGeneration(unsigned generation) { ChildGeneration = generation; } 0
705 DomTreeNode *node() { return Node; } 0
706 DomTreeNode::const_iterator childIter() const { return ChildIter; } 0
707 ----
708 DomTreeNode *nextChild() { 0
709 DomTreeNode *child = *ChildIter; 0
710 ++ChildIter; 0
711 return child; 0
712 } ----
713 ----
714 DomTreeNode::const_iterator end() const { return EndIter; } 0
715 bool isProcessed() const { return Processed; } 0
716 void process() { Processed = true; } 0
717 ----
718 private: ----
719 unsigned CurrentGeneration; ----
720 unsigned ChildGeneration; ----
721 DomTreeNode *Node; ----
722 DomTreeNode::const_iterator ChildIter; ----
723 DomTreeNode::const_iterator EndIter; ----
724 NodeScope Scopes; ----
725 bool Processed = false; ----
726 }; ----

728 /// Wrapper class to handle memory instructions, including loads, ----
729 /// stores and intrinsic loads and stores defined by the target. ----
730 class ParseMemoryInst { ----
731 public: ----
732 ParseMemoryInst(Instruction *Inst, const TargetTransformInfo &TTI) 0
733 : Inst(Inst) { 0
734 if (IntrinsicInst *II = dyn_cast(Inst)) { 0
735 IntrID = II->getIntrinsicID(); 0
736 if (TTI.getTgtMemIntrinsic(II, Info)) 0
737 return; 0
738 if (isHandledNonTargetIntrinsic(IntrID)) { 0
739 switch (IntrID) { 0
740 case Intrinsic::masked_load: 0
741 Info.PtrVal = Inst->getOperand(0); 0
742 Info.MatchingId = Intrinsic::masked_load; 0
743 Info.ReadMem = true; 0
744 Info.WriteMem = false; 0
745 Info.IsVolatile = false; 0
746 break; 0
747 case Intrinsic::masked_store: 0
748 Info.PtrVal = Inst->getOperand(1); 0
749 // Use the ID of masked load as the "matching id". This will ----
750 // prevent matching non-masked loads/stores with masked ones ----
751 // (which could be done), but at the moment, the code here ----
752 // does not support matching intrinsics with non-intrinsics, ----
753 // so keep the MatchingIds specific to masked instructions ----
754 // for now (TODO). ----
755 Info.MatchingId = Intrinsic::masked_load; 0
756 Info.ReadMem = false; 0
757 Info.WriteMem = true; 0
758 Info.IsVolatile = false; 0
759 break; 0
760 } ----
761 } ----
762 } ----
763 } ----
764 ----
765 Instruction *get() { return Inst; } 0
766 const Instruction *get() const { return Inst; } 0
767 ----
768 bool isLoad() const { 0
769 if (IntrID != 0) 0
770 return Info.ReadMem; 0
771 return isa(Inst); 0
772 } ----
773 ----
774 bool isStore() const { 0
775 if (IntrID != 0) 0
776 return Info.WriteMem; 0
777 return isa(Inst); 0
778 } ----
779 ----
780 bool isAtomic() const { 0
781 if (IntrID != 0) 0
782 return Info.Ordering != AtomicOrdering::NotAtomic; 0
783 return Inst->isAtomic(); 0
784 } ----
785 ----
786 bool isUnordered() const { 0
787 if (IntrID != 0) 0
788 return Info.isUnordered(); 0
789 ----
790 if (LoadInst *LI = dyn_cast(Inst)) { 0
791 return LI->isUnordered(); 0
792 } else if (StoreInst *SI = dyn_cast(Inst)) { 0
793 return SI->isUnordered(); 0
794 } ----
795 // Conservative answer ----
796 return !Inst->isAtomic(); 0
797 } ----
798 ----
799 bool isVolatile() const { 0
800 if (IntrID != 0) 0
801 return Info.IsVolatile; 0
802 ----
803 if (LoadInst *LI = dyn_cast(Inst)) { 0
804 return LI->isVolatile(); 0
805 } else if (StoreInst *SI = dyn_cast(Inst)) { 0
806 return SI->isVolatile(); 0
807 } ----
808 // Conservative answer ----
809 return true; 0
810 } ----
811 ----
812 bool isInvariantLoad() const { 0
813 if (auto *LI = dyn_cast(Inst)) 0
814 return LI->hasMetadata(LLVMContext::MD_invariant_load); 0
815 return false; 0
816 } ----
817 ----
818 bool isValid() const { return getPointerOperand() != nullptr; } 0
819 ----
820 // For regular (non-intrinsic) loads/stores, this is set to -1. For ----
821 // intrinsic loads/stores, the id is retrieved from the corresponding ----
822 // field in the MemIntrinsicInfo structure. That field contains ----
823 // non-negative values only. ----
824 int getMatchingId() const { 0
825 if (IntrID != 0) 0
826 return Info.MatchingId; 0
827 return -1; 0
828 } ----
829 ----
830 Value *getPointerOperand() const { 0
831 if (IntrID != 0) 0
832 return Info.PtrVal; 0
833 return getLoadStorePointerOperand(Inst); 0
834 } ----
835 ----
836 Type *getValueType() const { 0
837 // TODO: handle target-specific intrinsics. ----
838 return Inst->getAccessType(); 0
839 } ----
840 ----
841 bool mayReadFromMemory() const { 0
842 if (IntrID != 0) 0
843 return Info.ReadMem; 0
844 return Inst->mayReadFromMemory(); 0
845 } ----
846 ----
847 bool mayWriteToMemory() const { ----
848 if (IntrID != 0) ----
849 return Info.WriteMem; ----
850 return Inst->mayWriteToMemory(); ----
851 } ----
852 ----
853 private: ----
854 Intrinsic::ID IntrID = 0; ----
855 MemIntrinsicInfo Info; ----
856 Instruction *Inst; ----
857 }; ----

859 // This function is to prevent accidentally passing a non-target ----
860 // intrinsic ID to TargetTransformInfo. ----
861 static bool isHandledNonTargetIntrinsic(Intrinsic::ID ID) { 0
862 switch (ID) { 0
863 case Intrinsic::masked_load: 0
864 case Intrinsic::masked_store: ----
865 return true; 0
866 } ----
867 return false; 0
868 } ----
869 static bool isHandledNonTargetIntrinsic(const Value *V) { 0
870 if (auto *II = dyn_cast(V)) 0
871 return isHandledNonTargetIntrinsic(II->getIntrinsicID()); 0
872 return false; 0
873 } ----

886 Value *getOrCreateResult(Value *Inst, Type *ExpectedType) const { 0
887 // TODO: We could insert relevant casts on type mismatch here. ----
888 if (auto *LI = dyn_cast(Inst)) 0
889 return LI->getType() == ExpectedType ? LI : nullptr; 0
890 if (auto *SI = dyn_cast(Inst)) { 0
891 Value *V = SI->getValueOperand(); 0
892 return V->getType() == ExpectedType ? V : nullptr; 0
893 } ----
894 assert(isa(Inst) && "Instruction not supported"); 0
895 auto *II = cast(Inst); 0
896 if (isHandledNonTargetIntrinsic(II->getIntrinsicID())) 0
897 return getOrCreateResultNonTargetMemIntrinsic(II, ExpectedType); 0
898 return TTI.getOrCreateResultFromMemIntrinsic(II, ExpectedType); 0
899 } ----
900 ----
901 Value *getOrCreateResultNonTargetMemIntrinsic(IntrinsicInst *II, 0
902 Type *ExpectedType) const { ----
903 // TODO: We could insert relevant casts on type mismatch here. ----
904 switch (II->getIntrinsicID()) { 0
905 case Intrinsic::masked_load: 0
906 return II->getType() == ExpectedType ? II : nullptr; 0
907 case Intrinsic::masked_store: { 0
908 Value *V = II->getOperand(0); 0
909 return V->getType() == ExpectedType ? V : nullptr; 0
910 } ----
911 } ----
912 return nullptr; 0
913 } ----
914 ----
915 /// Return true if the instruction is known to only operate on memory ----
916 /// provably invariant in the given "generation". ----
917 bool isOperatingOnInvariantMemAt(Instruction *I, unsigned GenAt); ----
918 ----
919 bool isSameMemGeneration(unsigned EarlierGeneration, unsigned LaterGeneration, ----
920 Instruction *EarlierInst, Instruction *LaterInst); ----
921 ----
922 bool isNonTargetIntrinsicMatch(const IntrinsicInst *Earlier, 0
923 const IntrinsicInst *Later) { ----
924 auto IsSubmask = [](const Value *Mask0, const Value *Mask1) { 0
925 // Is Mask0 a submask of Mask1? ----
926 if (Mask0 == Mask1) 0
927 return true; 0
928 if (isa(Mask0) || isa(Mask1)) 0
929 return false; 0
930 auto *Vec0 = dyn_cast(Mask0); 0
931 auto *Vec1 = dyn_cast(Mask1); 0
932 if (!Vec0 || !Vec1) 0
933 return false; 0
934 if (Vec0->getType() != Vec1->getType()) 0
935 return false; 0
936 for (int i = 0, e = Vec0->getNumOperands(); i != e; ++i) { 0
937 Constant *Elem0 = Vec0->getOperand(i); 0
938 Constant *Elem1 = Vec1->getOperand(i); 0
939 auto *Int0 = dyn_cast(Elem0); 0
940 if (Int0 && Int0->isZero()) 0
941 continue; 0
942 auto *Int1 = dyn_cast(Elem1); 0
943 if (Int1 && !Int1->isZero()) 0
944 continue; 0
945 if (isa(Elem0) || isa(Elem1)) 0
946 return false; 0
947 if (Elem0 == Elem1) 0
948 continue; 0
949 return false; 0
950 } ----
951 return true; 0
952 }; ----
953 auto PtrOp = [](const IntrinsicInst *II) { 0
954 if (II->getIntrinsicID() == Intrinsic::masked_load) 0
955 return II->getOperand(0); 0
956 if (II->getIntrinsicID() == Intrinsic::masked_store) 0
957 return II->getOperand(1); 0
958 llvm_unreachable("Unexpected IntrinsicInst"); 0
959 }; ----
960 auto MaskOp = [](const IntrinsicInst *II) { 0
961 if (II->getIntrinsicID() == Intrinsic::masked_load) 0
962 return II->getOperand(2); 0
963 if (II->getIntrinsicID() == Intrinsic::masked_store) 0
964 return II->getOperand(3); 0
965 llvm_unreachable("Unexpected IntrinsicInst"); 0
966 }; ----
967 auto ThruOp = [](const IntrinsicInst *II) { 0
968 if (II->getIntrinsicID() == Intrinsic::masked_load) 0
969 return II->getOperand(3); 0
970 llvm_unreachable("Unexpected IntrinsicInst"); 0
971 }; ----
972 ----
973 if (PtrOp(Earlier) != PtrOp(Later)) 0
974 return false; 0
975 ----
976 Intrinsic::ID IDE = Earlier->getIntrinsicID(); 0
977 Intrinsic::ID IDL = Later->getIntrinsicID(); 0
978 // We could really use specific intrinsic classes for masked loads ----
979 // and stores in IntrinsicInst.h. ----
980 if (IDE == Intrinsic::masked_load && IDL == Intrinsic::masked_load) { 0
981 // Trying to replace later masked load with the earlier one. ----
982 // Check that the pointers are the same, and ----
983 // - masks and pass-throughs are the same, or ----
984 // - replacee's pass-through is "undef" and replacer's mask is a ----
985 // super-set of the replacee's mask. ----
986 if (MaskOp(Earlier) == MaskOp(Later) && ThruOp(Earlier) == ThruOp(Later)) 0
987 return true; 0
988 if (!isa(ThruOp(Later))) 0
989 return false; 0
990 return IsSubmask(MaskOp(Later), MaskOp(Earlier)); 0
991 } ----
992 if (IDE == Intrinsic::masked_store && IDL == Intrinsic::masked_load) { 0
993 // Trying to replace a load of a stored value with the store's value. ----
994 // Check that the pointers are the same, and ----
995 // - load's mask is a subset of store's mask, and ----
996 // - load's pass-through is "undef". ----
997 if (!IsSubmask(MaskOp(Later), MaskOp(Earlier))) 0
998 return false; 0
999 return isa(ThruOp(Later)); 0
1000 } ----
1001 if (IDE == Intrinsic::masked_load && IDL == Intrinsic::masked_store) { 0
1002 // Trying to remove a store of the loaded value. ----
1003 // Check that the pointers are the same, and ----
1004 // - store's mask is a subset of the load's mask. ----
1005 return IsSubmask(MaskOp(Later), MaskOp(Earlier)); 0
1006 } ----
1007 if (IDE == Intrinsic::masked_store && IDL == Intrinsic::masked_store) { 0
1008 // Trying to remove a dead store (earlier). ----
1009 // Check that the pointers are the same, ----
1010 // - the to-be-removed store's mask is a subset of the other store's ----
1011 // mask. ----
1012 return IsSubmask(MaskOp(Earlier), MaskOp(Later)); 0
1013 } ----
1014 return false; 0
1015 } ----
1016 ----
1017 void removeMSSA(Instruction &Inst) { 0
1018 if (!MSSA) 0
1019 return; 0
1020 if (VerifyMemorySSA) 0
1021 MSSA->verifyMemorySSA(); 0
1022 // Removing a store here can leave MemorySSA in an unoptimized state by ----
1023 // creating MemoryPhis that have identical arguments and by creating ----
1024 // MemoryUses whose defining access is not an actual clobber. The phi case ----
1025 // is handled by MemorySSA when passing OptimizePhis = true to ----
1026 // removeMemoryAccess. The non-optimized MemoryUse case is lazily updated ----
1027 // by MemorySSA's getClobberingMemoryAccess. ----
1028 MSSAUpdater->removeMemoryAccess(&Inst, true); 0
1029 } ----
1030 }; ----
1031 ----
1032 } // end anonymous namespace ----
1033 ----
1034 /// Determine if the memory referenced by LaterInst is from the same heap ----
1035 /// version as EarlierInst. ----
1036 /// This is currently called in two scenarios: ----
1037 /// ----
1038 /// load p ----
1039 /// ... ----
1040 /// load p ----
1041 /// ----
1042 /// and ----
1043 /// ----
1044 /// x = load p ----
1045 /// ... ----
1046 /// store x, p ----
1047 /// ----
1048 /// in both cases we want to verify that there are no possible writes to the ----
1049 /// memory referenced by p between the earlier and later instruction. ----
1050 bool EarlyCSE::isSameMemGeneration(unsigned EarlierGeneration, 0
1051 unsigned LaterGeneration, ----
1052 Instruction *EarlierInst, ----
1053 Instruction *LaterInst) { ----
1054 // Check the simple memory generation tracking first. ----
1055 if (EarlierGeneration == LaterGeneration) 0
1056 return true; 0
1057 ----
1058 if (!MSSA) 0
1059 return false; 0
1060 ----
1061 // If MemorySSA has determined that one of EarlierInst or LaterInst does not ----
1062 // read/write memory, then we can safely return true here. ----
1063 // FIXME: We could be more aggressive when checking doesNotAccessMemory(), ----
1064 // onlyReadsMemory(), mayReadFromMemory(), and mayWriteToMemory() in this pass ----
1065 // by also checking the MemorySSA MemoryAccess on the instruction. Initial ----
1066 // experiments suggest this isn't worthwhile, at least for C/C++ code compiled ----
1067 // with the default optimization pipeline. ----
1068 auto *EarlierMA = MSSA->getMemoryAccess(EarlierInst); 0
1069 if (!EarlierMA) 0
1070 return true; 0
1071 auto *LaterMA = MSSA->getMemoryAccess(LaterInst); 0
1072 if (!LaterMA) 0
1073 return true; 0
1074 ----
1075 // Since we know LaterDef dominates LaterInst and EarlierInst dominates ----
1076 // LaterInst, if LaterDef dominates EarlierInst then it can't occur between ----
1077 // EarlierInst and LaterInst and neither can any other write that potentially ----
1078 // clobbers LaterInst. ----
1079 MemoryAccess *LaterDef; ----
1080 if (ClobberCounter < EarlyCSEMssaOptCap) { 0
1081 LaterDef = MSSA->getWalker()->getClobberingMemoryAccess(LaterInst); 0
1082 ClobberCounter++; 0
1083 } else ----
1084 LaterDef = LaterMA->getDefiningAccess(); 0
1085 ----
1086 return MSSA->dominates(LaterDef, EarlierMA); 0
1087 } ----
1088 ----
1089 bool EarlyCSE::isOperatingOnInvariantMemAt(Instruction *I, unsigned GenAt) { 0
1090 // A location loaded from with an invariant_load is assumed to *never* change ----
1091 // within the visible scope of the compilation. ----
1092 if (auto *LI = dyn_cast(I)) 0
1093 if (LI->hasMetadata(LLVMContext::MD_invariant_load)) 0
1094 return true; 0
1095 ----
1096 auto MemLocOpt = MemoryLocation::getOrNone(I); 0
1097 if (!MemLocOpt) 0
1098 // "target" intrinsic forms of loads aren't currently known to ----
1099 // MemoryLocation::get. TODO ----
1100 return false; 0
1101 MemoryLocation MemLoc = *MemLocOpt; 0
1102 if (!AvailableInvariants.count(MemLoc)) 0
1103 return false; 0
1104 ----
1105 // Is the generation at which this became invariant older than the ----
1106 // current one? ----
1107 return AvailableInvariants.lookup(MemLoc) <= GenAt; 0
1108 } ----
1109 ----
1110 bool EarlyCSE::handleBranchCondition(Instruction *CondInst, 0
1111 const BranchInst *BI, const BasicBlock *BB, ----
1112 const BasicBlock *Pred) { ----
1113 assert(BI->isConditional() && "Should be a conditional branch!"); 0
1114 assert(BI->getCondition() == CondInst && "Wrong condition?"); 0
1115 assert(BI->getSuccessor(0) == BB || BI->getSuccessor(1) == BB); 0
1116 auto *TorF = (BI->getSuccessor(0) == BB) 0
1117 ? ConstantInt::getTrue(BB->getContext()) 0
1118 : ConstantInt::getFalse(BB->getContext()); 0
1119 auto MatchBinOp = [](Instruction *I, unsigned Opcode, Value *&LHS, 0
1120 Value *&RHS) { ----
1121 if (Opcode == Instruction::And && 0
1122 match(I, m_LogicalAnd(m_Value(LHS), m_Value(RHS)))) 0
1123 return true; 0
1124 else if (Opcode == Instruction::Or && 0
1125 match(I, m_LogicalOr(m_Value(LHS), m_Value(RHS)))) 0
1126 return true; 0
1127 return false; 0
1128 }; ----
1129 // If the condition is AND operation, we can propagate its operands into the ----
1130 // true branch. If it is OR operation, we can propagate them into the false ----
1131 // branch. ----
1132 unsigned PropagateOpcode = ----
1133 (BI->getSuccessor(0) == BB) ? Instruction::And : Instruction::Or; 0
1134 ----
1135 bool MadeChanges = false; 0
1136 SmallVector WorkList; 0
1137 SmallPtrSet Visited; 0
1138 WorkList.push_back(CondInst); 0
1139 while (!WorkList.empty()) { 0
1140 Instruction *Curr = WorkList.pop_back_val(); 0
1141 ----
1142 AvailableValues.insert(Curr, TorF); 0
1143 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << "EarlyCSE CVP: Add conditional value for '" 0
1144 << Curr->getName() << "' as " << *TorF << " in " ----
1145 << BB->getName() << "\n"); ----
1146 if (!DebugCounter::shouldExecute(CSECounter)) { 0
1147 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << "Skipping due to debug counter\n"); 0
1148 } else { ----
1149 // Replace all dominated uses with the known value. ----
1150 if (unsigned Count = replaceDominatedUsesWith(Curr, TorF, DT, 0
1151 BasicBlockEdge(Pred, BB))) { 0
1152 NumCSECVP += Count; 0
1153 MadeChanges = true; 0
1154 } ----
1155 } ----
1156 ----
1157 Value *LHS, *RHS; ----
1158 if (MatchBinOp(Curr, PropagateOpcode, LHS, RHS)) 0
1159 for (auto *Op : { LHS, RHS }) 0
1160 if (Instruction *OPI = dyn_cast(Op)) 0
1161 if (SimpleValue::canHandle(OPI) && Visited.insert(OPI).second) 0
1162 WorkList.push_back(OPI); 0
1163 } ----
1164 ----
1165 return MadeChanges; 0
1166 } 0
1167 ----
1168 Value *EarlyCSE::getMatchingValue(LoadValue &InVal, ParseMemoryInst &MemInst, 0
1169 unsigned CurrentGeneration) { ----
1170 if (InVal.DefInst == nullptr) 0
1171 return nullptr; 0
1172 if (InVal.MatchingId != MemInst.getMatchingId()) 0
1173 return nullptr; 0
1174 // We don't yet handle removing loads with ordering of any kind. ----
1175 if (MemInst.isVolatile() || !MemInst.isUnordered()) 0
1176 return nullptr; 0
1177 // We can't replace an atomic load with one which isn't also atomic. ----
1178 if (MemInst.isLoad() && !InVal.IsAtomic && MemInst.isAtomic()) 0
1179 return nullptr; 0
1180 // The value V returned from this function is used differently depending ----
1181 // on whether MemInst is a load or a store. If it's a load, we will replace ----
1182 // MemInst with V, if it's a store, we will check if V is the same as the ----
1183 // available value. ----
1184 bool MemInstMatching = !MemInst.isLoad(); 0
1185 Instruction *Matching = MemInstMatching ? MemInst.get() : InVal.DefInst; 0
1186 Instruction *Other = MemInstMatching ? InVal.DefInst : MemInst.get(); 0
1187 ----
1188 // For stores check the result values before checking memory generation ----
1189 // (otherwise isSameMemGeneration may crash). ----
1190 Value *Result = MemInst.isStore() 0
1191 ? getOrCreateResult(Matching, Other->getType()) 0
1192 : nullptr; 0
1193 if (MemInst.isStore() && InVal.DefInst != Result) 0
1194 return nullptr; 0
1195 ----
1196 // Deal with non-target memory intrinsics. ----
1197 bool MatchingNTI = isHandledNonTargetIntrinsic(Matching); 0
1198 bool OtherNTI = isHandledNonTargetIntrinsic(Other); 0
1199 if (OtherNTI != MatchingNTI) 0
1200 return nullptr; 0
1201 if (OtherNTI && MatchingNTI) { 0
1202 if (!isNonTargetIntrinsicMatch(cast(InVal.DefInst), 0
1203 cast(MemInst.get()))) 0
1204 return nullptr; 0
1205 } ----
1206 ----
1207 if (!isOperatingOnInvariantMemAt(MemInst.get(), InVal.Generation) && 0
1208 !isSameMemGeneration(InVal.Generation, CurrentGeneration, InVal.DefInst, 0
1209 MemInst.get())) ----
1210 return nullptr; 0
1211 ----
1212 if (!Result) 0
1213 Result = getOrCreateResult(Matching, Other->getType()); 0
1214 return Result; 0
1215 } ----
1216 ----
1217 bool EarlyCSE::overridingStores(const ParseMemoryInst &Earlier, 0
1218 const ParseMemoryInst &Later) { ----
1219 // Can we remove Earlier store because of Later store? ----
1220 ----
1221 assert(Earlier.isUnordered() && !Earlier.isVolatile() && 0
1222 "Violated invariant"); ----
1223 if (Earlier.getPointerOperand() != Later.getPointerOperand()) 0
1224 return false; 0
1225 if (!Earlier.getValueType() || !Later.getValueType() || 0
1226 Earlier.getValueType() != Later.getValueType()) 0
1227 return false; 0
1228 if (Earlier.getMatchingId() != Later.getMatchingId()) 0
1229 return false; 0
1230 // At the moment, we don't remove ordered stores, but do remove ----
1231 // unordered atomic stores. There's no special requirement (for ----
1232 // unordered atomics) about removing atomic stores only in favor of ----
1233 // other atomic stores since we were going to execute the non-atomic ----
1234 // one anyway and the atomic one might never have become visible. ----
1235 if (!Earlier.isUnordered() || !Later.isUnordered()) 0
1236 return false; 0
1237 ----
1238 // Deal with non-target memory intrinsics. ----
1239 bool ENTI = isHandledNonTargetIntrinsic(Earlier.get()); 0
1240 bool LNTI = isHandledNonTargetIntrinsic(Later.get()); 0
1241 if (ENTI && LNTI) 0
1242 return isNonTargetIntrinsicMatch(cast(Earlier.get()), 0
1243 cast(Later.get())); 0
1244 ----
1245 // Because of the check above, at least one of them is false. ----
1246 // For now disallow matching intrinsics with non-intrinsics, ----
1247 // so assume that the stores match if neither is an intrinsic. ----
1248 return ENTI == LNTI; 0
1249 } ----
1250 ----
1251 bool EarlyCSE::processNode(DomTreeNode *Node) { 0
1252 bool Changed = false; 0
1253 BasicBlock *BB = Node->getBlock(); 0
1254 ----
1255 // If this block has a single predecessor, then the predecessor is the parent ----
1256 // of the domtree node and all of the live out memory values are still current ----
1257 // in this block. If this block has multiple predecessors, then they could ----
1258 // have invalidated the live-out memory values of our parent value. For now, ----
1259 // just be conservative and invalidate memory if this block has multiple ----
1260 // predecessors. ----
1261 if (!BB->getSinglePredecessor()) 0
1262 ++CurrentGeneration; 0
1263 ----
1264 // If this node has a single predecessor which ends in a conditional branch, ----
1265 // we can infer the value of the branch condition given that we took this ----
1266 // path. We need the single predecessor to ensure there's not another path ----
1267 // which reaches this block where the condition might hold a different ----
1268 // value. Since we're adding this to the scoped hash table (like any other ----
1269 // def), it will have been popped if we encounter a future merge block. ----
1270 if (BasicBlock *Pred = BB->getSinglePredecessor()) { 0
1271 auto *BI = dyn_cast(Pred->getTerminator()); 0
1272 if (BI && BI->isConditional()) { 0
1273 auto *CondInst = dyn_cast(BI->getCondition()); 0
1274 if (CondInst && SimpleValue::canHandle(CondInst)) 0
1275 Changed |= handleBranchCondition(CondInst, BI, BB, Pred); 0
1276 } ----
1277 } ----
1278 ----
1279 /// LastStore - Keep track of the last non-volatile store that we saw... for ----
1280 /// as long as there in no instruction that reads memory. If we see a store ----
1281 /// to the same location, we delete the dead store. This zaps trivial dead ----
1282 /// stores which can occur in bitfield code among other things. ----
1283 Instruction *LastStore = nullptr; 0
1284 ----
1285 // See if any instructions in the block can be eliminated. If so, do it. If ----
1286 // not, add them to AvailableValues. ----
1287 for (Instruction &Inst : make_early_inc_range(*BB)) { 0
1288 // Dead instructions should just be removed. ----
1289 if (isInstructionTriviallyDead(&Inst, &TLI)) { 0
1290 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << "EarlyCSE DCE: " << Inst << '\n'); 0
1291 if (!DebugCounter::shouldExecute(CSECounter)) { 0
1292 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << "Skipping due to debug counter\n"); 0
1293 continue; 0
1294 } ----
1295 ----
1296 salvageKnowledge(&Inst, &AC); 0
1297 salvageDebugInfo(Inst); 0
1298 removeMSSA(Inst); 0
1299 Inst.eraseFromParent(); 0
1300 Changed = true; 0
1301 ++NumSimplify; 0
1302 continue; 0
1303 } ----
1304 ----
1305 // Skip assume intrinsics, they don't really have side effects (although ----
1306 // they're marked as such to ensure preservation of control dependencies), ----
1307 // and this pass will not bother with its removal. However, we should mark ----
1308 // its condition as true for all dominated blocks. ----
1309 if (auto *Assume = dyn_cast(&Inst)) { 0
1310 auto *CondI = dyn_cast(Assume->getArgOperand(0)); 0
1311 if (CondI && SimpleValue::canHandle(CondI)) { 0
1312 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << "EarlyCSE considering assumption: " << Inst 0
1313 << '\n'); ----
1314 AvailableValues.insert(CondI, ConstantInt::getTrue(BB->getContext())); 0
1315 } else ----
1316 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << "EarlyCSE skipping assumption: " << Inst << '\n'); 0
1317 continue; 0
1318 } 0
1319 ----
1320 // Likewise, noalias intrinsics don't actually write. ----
1321 if (match(&Inst, 0
1322 m_Intrinsic())) { 0
1323 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << "EarlyCSE skipping noalias intrinsic: " << Inst 0
1324 << '\n'); ----
1325 continue; 0
1326 } ----
1327 ----
1328 // Skip sideeffect intrinsics, for the same reason as assume intrinsics. ----
1329 if (match(&Inst, m_Intrinsic())) { 0
1330 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << "EarlyCSE skipping sideeffect: " << Inst << '\n'); 0
1331 continue; 0
1332 } ----
1333 ----
1334 // Skip pseudoprobe intrinsics, for the same reason as assume intrinsics. ----
1335 if (match(&Inst, m_Intrinsic())) { 0
1336 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << "EarlyCSE skipping pseudoprobe: " << Inst << '\n'); 0
1337 continue; 0
1338 } ----
1339 ----
1340 // We can skip all invariant.start intrinsics since they only read memory, ----
1341 // and we can forward values across it. For invariant starts without ----
1342 // invariant ends, we can use the fact that the invariantness never ends to ----
1343 // start a scope in the current generaton which is true for all future ----
1344 // generations. Also, we dont need to consume the last store since the ----
1345 // semantics of invariant.start allow us to perform DSE of the last ----
1346 // store, if there was a store following invariant.start. Consider: ----
1347 // ----
1348 // store 30, i8* p ----
1349 // invariant.start(p) ----
1350 // store 40, i8* p ----
1351 // We can DSE the store to 30, since the store 40 to invariant location p ----
1352 // causes undefined behaviour. ----
1353 if (match(&Inst, m_Intrinsic())) { 0
1354 // If there are any uses, the scope might end. ----
1355 if (!Inst.use_empty()) 0
1356 continue; 0
1357 MemoryLocation MemLoc = ----
1358 MemoryLocation::getForArgument(&cast(Inst), 1, TLI); 0
1359 // Don't start a scope if we already have a better one pushed ----
1360 if (!AvailableInvariants.count(MemLoc)) 0
1361 AvailableInvariants.insert(MemLoc, CurrentGeneration); 0
1362 continue; 0
1363 } 0
1364 ----
1365 if (isGuard(&Inst)) { 0
1366 if (auto *CondI = 0
1367 dyn_cast(cast(Inst).getArgOperand(0))) { 0
1368 if (SimpleValue::canHandle(CondI)) { 0
1369 // Do we already know the actual value of this condition? ----
1370 if (auto *KnownCond = AvailableValues.lookup(CondI)) { 0
1371 // Is the condition known to be true? ----
1372 if (isa(KnownCond) && 0
1373 cast(KnownCond)->isOne()) { 0
1374 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() 0
1375 << "EarlyCSE removing guard: " << Inst << '\n'); ----
1376 salvageKnowledge(&Inst, &AC); 0
1377 removeMSSA(Inst); 0
1378 Inst.eraseFromParent(); 0
1379 Changed = true; 0
1380 continue; 0
1381 } else ----
1382 // Use the known value if it wasn't true. ----
1383 cast(Inst).setArgOperand(0, KnownCond); 0
1384 } ----
1385 // The condition we're on guarding here is true for all dominated ----
1386 // locations. ----
1387 AvailableValues.insert(CondI, ConstantInt::getTrue(BB->getContext())); 0
1388 } ----
1389 } ----
1390 ----
1391 // Guard intrinsics read all memory, but don't write any memory. ----
1392 // Accordingly, don't update the generation but consume the last store (to ----
1393 // avoid an incorrect DSE). ----
1394 LastStore = nullptr; 0
1395 continue; 0
1396 } 0
1397 ----
1398 // If the instruction can be simplified (e.g. X+0 = X) then replace it with ----
1399 // its simpler value. ----
1400 if (Value *V = simplifyInstruction(&Inst, SQ)) { 0
1401 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << "EarlyCSE Simplify: " << Inst << " to: " << *V 0
1402 << '\n'); ----
1403 if (!DebugCounter::shouldExecute(CSECounter)) { 0
1404 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << "Skipping due to debug counter\n"); 0
1405 } else { ----
1406 bool Killed = false; 0
1407 if (!Inst.use_empty()) { 0
1408 Inst.replaceAllUsesWith(V); 0
1409 Changed = true; 0
1410 } ----
1411 if (isInstructionTriviallyDead(&Inst, &TLI)) { 0
1412 salvageKnowledge(&Inst, &AC); 0
1413 removeMSSA(Inst); 0
1414 Inst.eraseFromParent(); 0
1415 Changed = true; 0
1416 Killed = true; 0
1417 } ----
1418 if (Changed) 0
1419 ++NumSimplify; 0
1420 if (Killed) 0
1421 continue; 0
1422 } ----
1423 } ----
1424 ----
1425 // If this is a simple instruction that we can value number, process it. ----
1426 if (SimpleValue::canHandle(&Inst)) { 0
1427 if (auto *CI = dyn_cast(&Inst)) { 0
1428 assert(CI->getExceptionBehavior() != fp::ebStrict && 0
1429 "Unexpected ebStrict from SimpleValue::canHandle()"); ----
1430 assert((!CI->getRoundingMode() || 0
1431 CI->getRoundingMode() != RoundingMode::Dynamic) && ----
1432 "Unexpected dynamic rounding from SimpleValue::canHandle()"); ----
1433 } ----
1434 // See if the instruction has an available value. If so, use it. ----
1435 if (Value *V = AvailableValues.lookup(&Inst)) { 0
1436 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << "EarlyCSE CSE: " << Inst << " to: " << *V 0
1437 << '\n'); ----
1438 if (!DebugCounter::shouldExecute(CSECounter)) { 0
1439 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << "Skipping due to debug counter\n"); 0
1440 continue; 0
1441 } ----
1442 if (auto *I = dyn_cast(V)) { 0
1443 // If I being poison triggers UB, there is no need to drop those ----
1444 // flags. Otherwise, only retain flags present on both I and Inst. ----
1445 // TODO: Currently some fast-math flags are not treated as ----
1446 // poison-generating even though they should. Until this is fixed, ----
1447 // always retain flags present on both I and Inst for floating point ----
1448 // instructions. ----
1449 if (isa(I) || (I->hasPoisonGeneratingFlags() && !programUndefinedIfPoison(I))) 0
1450 I->andIRFlags(&Inst); 0
1451 } ----
1452 Inst.replaceAllUsesWith(V); 0
1453 salvageKnowledge(&Inst, &AC); 0
1454 removeMSSA(Inst); 0
1455 Inst.eraseFromParent(); 0
1456 Changed = true; 0
1457 ++NumCSE; 0
1458 continue; 0
1459 } 0
1460 ----
1461 // Otherwise, just remember that this value is available. ----
1462 AvailableValues.insert(&Inst, &Inst); 0
1463 continue; 0
1464 } 0
1465 ----
1466 ParseMemoryInst MemInst(&Inst, TTI); 0
1467 // If this is a non-volatile load, process it. ----
1468 if (MemInst.isValid() && MemInst.isLoad()) { 0
1469 // (conservatively) we can't peak past the ordering implied by this ----
1470 // operation, but we can add this load to our set of available values ----
1471 if (MemInst.isVolatile() || !MemInst.isUnordered()) { 0
1472 LastStore = nullptr; 0
1473 ++CurrentGeneration; 0
1474 } ----
1475 ----
1476 if (MemInst.isInvariantLoad()) { 0
1477 // If we pass an invariant load, we know that memory location is ----
1478 // indefinitely constant from the moment of first dereferenceability. ----
1479 // We conservatively treat the invariant_load as that moment. If we ----
1480 // pass a invariant load after already establishing a scope, don't ----
1481 // restart it since we want to preserve the earliest point seen. ----
1482 auto MemLoc = MemoryLocation::get(&Inst); 0
1483 if (!AvailableInvariants.count(MemLoc)) 0
1484 AvailableInvariants.insert(MemLoc, CurrentGeneration); 0
1485 } ----
1486 ----
1487 // If we have an available version of this load, and if it is the right ----
1488 // generation or the load is known to be from an invariant location, ----
1489 // replace this instruction. ----
1490 // ----
1491 // If either the dominating load or the current load are invariant, then ----
1492 // we can assume the current load loads the same value as the dominating ----
1493 // load. ----
1494 LoadValue InVal = AvailableLoads.lookup(MemInst.getPointerOperand()); 0
1495 if (Value *Op = getMatchingValue(InVal, MemInst, CurrentGeneration)) { 0
1496 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << "EarlyCSE CSE LOAD: " << Inst 0
1497 << " to: " << *InVal.DefInst << '\n'); ----
1498 if (!DebugCounter::shouldExecute(CSECounter)) { 0
1499 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << "Skipping due to debug counter\n"); 0
1500 continue; 0
1501 } ----
1502 if (InVal.IsLoad) 0
1503 if (auto *I = dyn_cast(Op)) 0
1504 combineMetadataForCSE(I, &Inst, false); 0
1505 if (!Inst.use_empty()) 0
1506 Inst.replaceAllUsesWith(Op); 0
1507 salvageKnowledge(&Inst, &AC); 0
1508 removeMSSA(Inst); 0
1509 Inst.eraseFromParent(); 0
1510 Changed = true; 0
1511 ++NumCSELoad; 0
1512 continue; 0
1513 } 0
1514 ----
1515 // Otherwise, remember that we have this instruction. ----
1516 AvailableLoads.insert(MemInst.getPointerOperand(), 0
1517 LoadValue(&Inst, CurrentGeneration, 0
1518 MemInst.getMatchingId(), 0
1519 MemInst.isAtomic(), 0
1520 MemInst.isLoad())); 0
1521 LastStore = nullptr; 0
1522 continue; 0
1523 } 0
1524 ----
1525 // If this instruction may read from memory or throw (and potentially read ----
1526 // from memory in the exception handler), forget LastStore. Load/store ----
1527 // intrinsics will indicate both a read and a write to memory. The target ----
1528 // may override this (e.g. so that a store intrinsic does not read from ----
1529 // memory, and thus will be treated the same as a regular store for ----
1530 // commoning purposes). ----
1531 if ((Inst.mayReadFromMemory() || Inst.mayThrow()) && 0
1532 !(MemInst.isValid() && !MemInst.mayReadFromMemory())) 0
1533 LastStore = nullptr; 0
1534 ----
1535 // If this is a read-only call, process it. ----
1536 if (CallValue::canHandle(&Inst)) { 0
1537 // If we have an available version of this call, and if it is the right ----
1538 // generation, replace this instruction. ----
1539 std::pair InVal = AvailableCalls.lookup(&Inst); 0
1540 if (InVal.first != nullptr && 0
1541 isSameMemGeneration(InVal.second, CurrentGeneration, InVal.first, 0
1542 &Inst)) { ----
1543 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << "EarlyCSE CSE CALL: " << Inst 0
1544 << " to: " << *InVal.first << '\n'); ----
1545 if (!DebugCounter::shouldExecute(CSECounter)) { 0
1546 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << "Skipping due to debug counter\n"); 0
1547 continue; 0
1548 } ----
1549 if (!Inst.use_empty()) 0
1550 Inst.replaceAllUsesWith(InVal.first); 0
1551 salvageKnowledge(&Inst, &AC); 0
1552 removeMSSA(Inst); 0
1553 Inst.eraseFromParent(); 0
1554 Changed = true; 0
1555 ++NumCSECall; 0
1556 continue; 0
1557 } ----
1558 ----
1559 // Otherwise, remember that we have this instruction. ----
1560 AvailableCalls.insert(&Inst, std::make_pair(&Inst, CurrentGeneration)); 0
1561 continue; 0
1562 } 0
1563 ----
1564 // A release fence requires that all stores complete before it, but does ----
1565 // not prevent the reordering of following loads 'before' the fence. As a ----
1566 // result, we don't need to consider it as writing to memory and don't need ----
1567 // to advance the generation. We do need to prevent DSE across the fence, ----
1568 // but that's handled above. ----
1569 if (auto *FI = dyn_cast(&Inst)) 0
1570 if (FI->getOrdering() == AtomicOrdering::Release) { 0
1571 assert(Inst.mayReadFromMemory() && "relied on to prevent DSE above"); 0
1572 continue; 0
1573 } ----
1574 ----
1575 // write back DSE - If we write back the same value we just loaded from ----
1576 // the same location and haven't passed any intervening writes or ordering ----
1577 // operations, we can remove the write. The primary benefit is in allowing ----
1578 // the available load table to remain valid and value forward past where ----
1579 // the store originally was. ----
1580 if (MemInst.isValid() && MemInst.isStore()) { 0
1581 LoadValue InVal = AvailableLoads.lookup(MemInst.getPointerOperand()); 0
1582 if (InVal.DefInst && 0
1583 InVal.DefInst == getMatchingValue(InVal, MemInst, CurrentGeneration)) { 0
1584 // It is okay to have a LastStore to a different pointer here if MemorySSA ----
1585 // tells us that the load and store are from the same memory generation. ----
1586 // In that case, LastStore should keep its present value since we're ----
1587 // removing the current store. ----
1588 assert((!LastStore || 0
1589 ParseMemoryInst(LastStore, TTI).getPointerOperand() == ----
1590 MemInst.getPointerOperand() || ----
1591 MSSA) && ----
1592 "can't have an intervening store if not using MemorySSA!"); ----
1593 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << "EarlyCSE DSE (writeback): " << Inst << '\n'); 0
1594 if (!DebugCounter::shouldExecute(CSECounter)) { 0
1595 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << "Skipping due to debug counter\n"); 0
1596 continue; 0
1597 } ----
1598 salvageKnowledge(&Inst, &AC); 0
1599 removeMSSA(Inst); 0
1600 Inst.eraseFromParent(); 0
1601 Changed = true; 0
1602 ++NumDSE; 0
1603 // We can avoid incrementing the generation count since we were able ----
1604 // to eliminate this store. ----
1605 continue; 0
1606 } ----
1607 } ----
1608 ----
1609 // Okay, this isn't something we can CSE at all. Check to see if it is ----
1610 // something that could modify memory. If so, our available memory values ----
1611 // cannot be used so bump the generation count. ----
1612 if (Inst.mayWriteToMemory()) { 0
1613 ++CurrentGeneration; 0
1614 ----
1615 if (MemInst.isValid() && MemInst.isStore()) { 0
1616 // We do a trivial form of DSE if there are two stores to the same ----
1617 // location with no intervening loads. Delete the earlier store. ----
1618 if (LastStore) { 0
1619 if (overridingStores(ParseMemoryInst(LastStore, TTI), MemInst)) { 0
1620 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << "EarlyCSE DEAD STORE: " << *LastStore 0
1621 << " due to: " << Inst << '\n'); ----
1622 if (!DebugCounter::shouldExecute(CSECounter)) { 0
1623 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << "Skipping due to debug counter\n"); 0
1624 } else { ----
1625 salvageKnowledge(&Inst, &AC); 0
1626 removeMSSA(*LastStore); 0
1627 LastStore->eraseFromParent(); 0
1628 Changed = true; 0
1629 ++NumDSE; 0
1630 LastStore = nullptr; 0
1631 } ----
1632 } ----
1633 // fallthrough - we can exploit information about this store ----
1634 } ----
1635 ----
1636 // Okay, we just invalidated anything we knew about loaded values. Try ----
1637 // to salvage *something* by remembering that the stored value is a live ----
1638 // version of the pointer. It is safe to forward from volatile stores ----
1639 // to non-volatile loads, so we don't have to check for volatility of ----
1640 // the store. ----
1641 AvailableLoads.insert(MemInst.getPointerOperand(), 0
1642 LoadValue(&Inst, CurrentGeneration, 0
1643 MemInst.getMatchingId(), 0
1644 MemInst.isAtomic(), 0
1645 MemInst.isLoad())); 0
1646 ----
1647 // Remember that this was the last unordered store we saw for DSE. We ----
1648 // don't yet handle DSE on ordered or volatile stores since we don't ----
1649 // have a good way to model the ordering requirement for following ----
1650 // passes once the store is removed. We could insert a fence, but ----
1651 // since fences are slightly stronger than stores in their ordering, ----
1652 // it's not clear this is a profitable transform. Another option would ----
1653 // be to merge the ordering with that of the post dominating store. ----
1654 if (MemInst.isUnordered() && !MemInst.isVolatile()) 0
1655 LastStore = &Inst; 0
1656 else ----
1657 LastStore = nullptr; 0
1658 } ----
1659 } ----
1660 } ----
1661 ----
1662 return Changed; 0
1663 } ----
1664 ----
1665 bool EarlyCSE::run() { 0
1666 // Note, deque is being used here because there is significant performance ----
1667 // gains over vector when the container becomes very large due to the ----
1668 // specific access patterns. For more information see the mailing list ----
1669 // discussion on this: ----
1670 // http://lists.llvm.org/pipermail/llvm-commits/Week-of-Mon-20120116/135228.html ----
1671 std::deque nodesToProcess; 0
1672 ----
1673 bool Changed = false; 0
1674 ----
1675 // Process the root node. ----
1676 nodesToProcess.push_back(new StackNode( 0
1677 AvailableValues, AvailableLoads, AvailableInvariants, AvailableCalls, 0
1678 CurrentGeneration, DT.getRootNode(), 0
1679 DT.getRootNode()->begin(), DT.getRootNode()->end())); 0
1680 ----
1681 assert(!CurrentGeneration && "Create a new EarlyCSE instance to rerun it."); 0
1682 ----
1683 // Process the stack. ----
1684 while (!nodesToProcess.empty()) { 0
1685 // Grab the first item off the stack. Set the current generation, remove ----
1686 // the node from the stack, and process it. ----
1687 StackNode *NodeToProcess = nodesToProcess.back(); 0
1688 ----
1689 // Initialize class members. ----
1690 CurrentGeneration = NodeToProcess->currentGeneration(); 0
1691 ----
1692 // Check if the node needs to be processed. ----
1693 if (!NodeToProcess->isProcessed()) { 0
1694 // Process the node. ----
1695 Changed |= processNode(NodeToProcess->node()); 0
1696 NodeToProcess->childGeneration(CurrentGeneration); 0
1697 NodeToProcess->process(); 0
1698 } else if (NodeToProcess->childIter() != NodeToProcess->end()) { 0
1699 // Push the next child onto the stack. ----
1700 DomTreeNode *child = NodeToProcess->nextChild(); 0
1701 nodesToProcess.push_back( 0
1702 new StackNode(AvailableValues, AvailableLoads, AvailableInvariants, 0
1703 AvailableCalls, NodeToProcess->childGeneration(), 0
1704 child, child->begin(), child->end())); 0
1705 } else { ----
1706 // It has been processed, and there are no more children to process, ----
1707 // so delete it and pop it off the stack. ----
1708 delete NodeToProcess; 0
1709 nodesToProcess.pop_back(); 0
1710 } ----
1711 } // while (!nodes...) ----
1712 ----
1713 return Changed; 0
1714 } 0
1715 ----
1716 PreservedAnalyses EarlyCSEPass::run(Function &F, 0
1717 FunctionAnalysisManager &AM) { ----
1718 auto &TLI = AM.getResult(F); 0
1719 auto &TTI = AM.getResult(F); 0
1720 auto &DT = AM.getResult(F); 0
1721 auto &AC = AM.getResult(F); 0
1722 auto *MSSA = ----
1723 UseMemorySSA ? &AM.getResult(F).getMSSA() : nullptr; 0
1724 ----
1725 EarlyCSE CSE(F.getParent()->getDataLayout(), TLI, TTI, DT, AC, MSSA); 0
1726 ----
1727 if (!CSE.run()) 0
1728 return PreservedAnalyses::all(); 0
1729 ----
1730 PreservedAnalyses PA; 0
1731 PA.preserveSet(); 0
1732 if (UseMemorySSA) 0
1733 PA.preserve(); 0
1734 return PA; 0
1735 } 0
1736 ----
1737 void EarlyCSEPass::printPipeline( 0
1738 raw_ostream &OS, function_ref MapClassName2PassName) { ----
1739 static_cast *>(this)->printPipeline( 0
1740 OS, MapClassName2PassName); ----
1741 OS << '<'; 0
1742 if (UseMemorySSA) 0
1743 OS << "memssa"; 0
1744 OS << '>'; 0
1745 } 0
1746 ----
1747 namespace { ----
1748 ----
1749 /// A simple and fast domtree-based CSE pass. ----
1750 /// ----
1751 /// This pass does a simple depth-first walk over the dominator tree, ----
1752 /// eliminating trivially redundant instructions and using instsimplify to ----
1753 /// canonicalize things as it goes. It is intended to be fast and catch obvious ----
1754 /// cases so that instcombine and other passes are more effective. It is ----
1755 /// expected that a later pass of GVN will catch the interesting/hard cases. ----
1756 template ----
1757 class EarlyCSELegacyCommonPass : public FunctionPass { ----
1758 public: ----
1759 static char ID; ----
1760 ----
1761 EarlyCSELegacyCommonPass() : FunctionPass(ID) { 0
1762 if (UseMemorySSA) ----
1763 initializeEarlyCSEMemSSALegacyPassPass(*PassRegistry::getPassRegistry()); 0
1764 else ----
1765 initializeEarlyCSELegacyPassPass(*PassRegistry::getPassRegistry()); 0
1766 } 0
1767 ----
1768 bool runOnFunction(Function &F) override { 0
1769 if (skipFunction(F)) 0
1770 return false; 0
1771 ----
1772 auto &TLI = getAnalysis().getTLI(F); 0
1773 auto &TTI = getAnalysis().getTTI(F); 0
1774 auto &DT = getAnalysis().getDomTree(); 0
1775 auto &AC = getAnalysis().getAssumptionCache(F); 0
1776 auto *MSSA = 0
1777 UseMemorySSA ? &getAnalysis().getMSSA() : nullptr; 0
1778 ----
